[In the past week there has been 1 new case of cVDPV1 in Papua New Guinea in a new province (see Poliomyelitis update (33): Papua New Guinea (EG) 20180806.5950667 for more details on this case); 1 new isolate of a cVDPV2 in a community contact in Yobe State, Nigeria; and 4 WPV1 isolates in environmental samples from Punjab Province, Sindh Province, and Karachi city (also located in Sindh province).

My interpretations haven't changed from previous comments: the vaccine virus is in competition with the WPV for which viruses are stumbling blocks to achieving polio eradication. The verdict isn't in as yet, but sticking my neck out on the chopping block, I suspect we are getting much closer to interrupting transmission of WPV1 in Pakistan and Afghanistan than we are in identifying all foci of cVDPV activity globally and interrupting the transmission of these viruses.

A map showing the global locations of WPV1 and cVDPV cases of polio can be found at http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

