******
[2] El Salvador, OPV3 virus, RFI
Date: Thu 9 Aug 2018
Source: El Salvador.com [trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
https://www.elsalvador.com/noticias/nacional/507984/salud-investiga-caso-sospechoso-de-poliomielitis/


The last confirmed case of the disease [polio] occurred in 1987; for this reason, the Ministry of Health is investigating what is happening.

A 10 year old boy with acute flaccid paralysis [AFP] and suspected to have poliomyelitis is in a "critical situation", the vice minister of health policies of the Ministry of Health (Minsal), Eduardo Espinoza, said yesterday [Wed 8 Aug 2018] at a television interview. The case is under review by the health authorities because, in the past 31 years, there have not been any cases of polio reported in El Salvador.

The child is from the canton of Los Llanitos, from Ilobasco, in Cabanas, and is admitted in the Bloom Hospital since 28 Jun 2018. The patient was examined in this country; specimens taken were sent to the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta, [Georgia], USA.

Although the CDC reported the presence of a type 3 Sabin virus, this does not mean that this virus is necessarily the cause of the clinical picture presented by the child, because the child received the routine vaccinations.

For the health official, the spinal fluid analysis, the haematological laboratory analysis, the tests sent to the CDC of Atlanta, and the notification made by the International Regulation from Washington [presumably the IHR - international health regulations requiring reporting through PAHO] leads to the conclusion that "this should be treated as a Guillain Barre syndrome [GBS] with the coincidental presence. of poliovirus 3, but it is not the polio virus that has caused the disease in the child. That is completely clear," said Espinoza. In addition, there is a waiting period of 60 days, counting from when the child began his clinical illness, to be sure that it is not a polio case.

The official did not rule out that this could be a case of vaccine-associated [paralytic] poliomyelitis, because the child had contact with the attenuated virus type 3 [OPV3] found in the polio vaccine taken. "This child, who was vaccinated 6 years ago, may have ingested the vaccine virus, but the vaccine virus does not cause the disease, except in the very rarest of cases, approximately 1 in every 2 million children vaccinated. The vaccine virus may have some manifestations like polio, but it is mild. In this case, the analysis showed that there was contact with this vaccine virus that probably came from a child who was recently vaccinated."

The declarations of Espinoza coincide with those of the infectious disease doctor, Jorge Panameno, who explained the results express that the child had contact with the virus, but that "there is less risk that an epidemic occurs, unlike when there are wild viruses."

There are 2 categories of virus: the wild poliovirus [WPV], which circulates naturally, and a vaccine-originated virus, which is produced by the live attenuated viruses found in the doses taken.

According to WHO, the attenuated vaccine virus multiplies in the intestine for a limited time, generating the production of antibodies that confer immunity. The vaccine virus is also excreted in the stool. In areas with inadequate sanitation, the excreted vaccine virus can spread to the nearby community, and this can confer protection to other children through indirect immunization. While in rare cases, when the population is significantly under-immunized, the excreted vaccine virus can continue to circulate for a longer period; in even rarer cases, vaccine viruses can undergo genetic changes that confer the ability to produce paralysis.

Panameno explained that, in the case that the virus is vaccine-derived, 2 interpretations must be made. "The 1st interpretation is that vaccination levels are low, and proper vaccination coverage has not been maintained. The 2nd is the terrible conditions in which the population that suffers from these diseases lives."

For Panameno, typhoid fever, hepatitis A, and poliomyelitis are diseases that have fecal-oral transmission in common. "That means that the Salvadorian population is consuming water that is contaminated with human feces and probably also foods [are contaminated]." Panameno called on the parents of families to review their children's vaccination records, in addition to working towards prevention of diseases transmitted through the fecal-oral route through taking hygienic means.

[byline: Evelia Hernandez]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed-esp@promedmail.org>

[This is now the 2nd case of an AFP syndrome presenting in a child in the Americas region in whom an OPV3 virus has been isolated. In the 1st instance, the child was an unvaccinated child who resided in a remote indigenous community of Venezuela that recently had a vaccination campaign (see Poliomyelitis update (21): global (Pakistan, Venezuela) PAHO update 20180616.5858106, Poliomyelitis update (19): Venezuela, vaccine virus found, VAPP susp 20180609.5848416, and Poliomyelitis update (17): Venezuela, cases conf. global (Pakistan), RFI 20180607.5845259 for details). In this current incident, the child is a 10 year old with a history of having reportedly completed the full polio vaccination series, presenting with an apparent GBS clinical picture (acute onset of ascending paralysis and usually sensory deficit), in whom an OPV3 virus was isolated. Recognizing that vaccine-associated paralytic polio (VAPP) cases can be detrimental to a country's vaccination program, serving as fuel for anti-vaxxers in the communities, it is still hard to understand how the isolation of a vaccine virus in a case of an AFP presentation is categorically ruled out as not being related to the vaccine virus. To date, I have not heard of another etiology for the AFP presentation in the Venezuelan case, and more information is still pending on the current case in El Salvador.

Wondering if I am missing something here, I ran to the literature and found an excellent review article on VAPP cases (see ref 1 below), but, more importantly, found an MMWR article describing an imported case of VAPP in a returning tourist in 2005. In this article there was mention that "the isolation of Sabin-strain polioviruses types 2 and 3 from a stool specimen and absence of isolation or serologic evidence for infection with another agent known to cause polio-like symptoms (for example, West Nile virus or enterovirus 71) is consistent with VAPP. A panel of polio experts convened by CDC confirmed this case to be paralytic polio on the basis of standard clinical evidence, and the case was classified as imported VAPP with onset of illness within 30 days before entry into the United States, in accordance with CDC protocol."

Landaverde et al (ref 3) did a review of AFP cases reported in Latin America and the Caribbean: "Cases with an onset of paralysis occurring 4-40 days following OPV administration were defined as recipient VAPP (group A). .... potential recipient cases with viral isolation but with an unknown status of residual paralysis were also classified as recipient VAPP (group B). Cases with an unknown status or date of OPV receipt or with an onset of paralysis outside the 4-40-day interval were defined as nonrecipient VAPP (group C). The term 'nonrecipient VAPP' includes contact cases mentioned in other studies and potential recipient cases with unknown dates of OPV administration. Potential nonrecipient cases with viral isolation and with an unknown status of residual paralysis were added if they were diagnosed as VAPP in the field (group D)." In those individuals in group C they calculated a risk of 1 case per 13.84 million doses of vaccine administered (1 case per 11.63-17.09 million). So my question remains: Was an alternative explanation/diagnosis made for the child in Venezuela to rule out a diagnosis of VAPP, and, moving forward, will there be an alternative diagnosis made for the child in El Salvador to rule out this being a case of VAPP? And with the occurrence of 2 cases of an OPV3 virus identified in less than 3 months, should we be concerned about the lots of vaccine in use?

Furthermore, in these cases of isolation of OPV viruses in AFP cases, should further studies be done using mouse models testing the neurovirulence of the isolate as done by Thorley et al. in ref. 4?

References:
1. Platt LR, Estivariz CF, Sutter RW. Vaccine-associated paralytic poliomyelitis: a review of the epidemiology and estimation of the global burden. J Infect Dis. 2014 Nov 1; 210 Suppl 1: S380-9. doi: 10.1093/infdis/jiu184 https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/210/suppl_1/S380/2194388.
2. CDC. Imported vaccine-associated paralytic poliomyelitis-United States, 2005. MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep. 2006 Feb 3; 55(4): 97-9. https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5504a2.htm.
3. Landaverde JM, Trumbo SP, Danovaro-Holliday MC, Cochi SE, Gandhi R, Ruiz-Matus C. Vaccine-associated paralytic poliomyelitis in the postelimination era in Latin America and the Caribbean, 1992-2011. J Infect Dis. 2014 May 1; 209(9): 1393-402. doi: 10.1093/infdis/jit602. Epub 2014 Feb 11. https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/209/9/1393/885238.
4.Thorley B, Kelly H, Nishimura Y, Yoon YK, Brussen KA, Roberts J, et al. Oral poliovirus vaccine type 3 from a patient with transverse myelitis is neurovirulent in a transgenic mouse model. J Clin Virol. 2009 Apr; 44(4): 268-71. doi: 10.1016/j.jcv.2009.01.014. Epub 2009 Mar 9. Abstract available at https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19269246.

A map of El Salvador showing departments can be found at http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/el_salvador_map.htm.

